Sure! Compose is a new way to build user interfaces (UI) in Kotlin using a declarative approach. With Compose, rather than working with Android's traditional view hierarchy and XML layout files, you use a set of composable functions to describe your UI components. Here's a quick tutorial to get you started with Compose:

1. Add Compose to your project: 
   To use Compose, you need to add the dependencies to your Gradle file. Add the following lines in your app build.gradle file:

   ```
   android {
       ...
       buildFeatures {
           compose true
       }
   }

   dependencies {
       ...
       implementation 'androidx.compose.ui:ui:1.0.2'
       implementation 'androidx.compose.material:material:1.0.2'
       implementation 'androidx.compose.runtime:runtime-livedata:1.0.2'
   }
   ```

   These dependencies will enable you to use the UI and Material components libraries, as well as the LiveData integration. After syncing your project with Gradle, you're ready to start composing!

2. Create a composable function: 
   A composable function is a regular Kotlin function that returns a UI component. To create your first composable function, add the following code to your MainActivity.kt file:

   ```
   import androidx.compose.material.Text
   import androidx.compose.runtime.Composable
   import androidx.compose.ui.tooling.preview.Preview

   @Composable
   fun Greeting(name: String) {
       Text(text = "Hello $name!")
   }

   @Preview
   @Composable
   fun PreviewGreeting() {
       Greeting(name = "World")
   }
   ```

   In this example, the `Greeting` function takes a `name` argument and returns a `Text` component with a greeting message. The `PreviewGreeting` function generates a preview of the `Greeting` function with the "World" argument.

3. Display the composable function: 
   To display the `Greeting` composable function in your MainActivity, add the following code to the onCreate method:

   ```
   setContent {
       Greeting(name = "Compose")
   }
   ```

   This sets the content view of the Activity to the `Greeting` function with the "Compose" argument.

That's it! You've just created and displayed your first Compose UI component. There is much more to Compose, including layout and state management, that you can learn about in the official documentation. Hope this helps!

The `elevation` parameter in the `Card` composable specifies the shadow depth of the card, and it takes a `Dp` value as its argument. The valid range of the `Dp` value is 0-24, and larger values correspond to higher shadows.

Here's an example of how to set the elevation of a card:

```
Card(
    modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth().padding(16.dp),
    elevation = 8.dp,
    shape = MaterialTheme.shapes.medium
) {
    // card content
}
```

In this example, the `elevation` parameter is set to `8.dp`, which will create a card with a shadow depth of 8 density pixels. You can experiment with different shadow depths to achieve the desired visual effect.

Note that the `Card` composable only adds a shadow on Android 5.0 (API level 21) and higher. On earlier versions of Android, the shadow will not be rendered.

