You can preview a composable function using the `@Preview` annotation in Compose. Here's an example of how to add a preview to a composable function:

```
import androidx.compose.runtime.Composable
import androidx.compose.ui.tooling.preview.Preview

@Composable
fun MyComposable(message: String) {
    Text(text = message)
}

@Preview
@Composable
fun MyComposablePreview() {
    MyComposable(message = "Hello, World!")
}
```

In this example, we have a `MyComposable` function that takes a `message` parameter and returns a `Text` component. To add a preview to the function, we use the `@Preview` annotation before the preview function, which generates a preview of the composable function. 

Then, in the preview function, we call the `MyComposable` with some sample data, such as "Hello, World!".

You can use the Preview tool window in Android Studio to preview your composable function. To open the Preview tool window, go to View -> Tool Windows -> Preview. 

In the Preview tool window, you should see a preview of your composable function with the sample data you provided. You can interact with the preview just like it's a live UI component.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

This error occurs because Compose doesn't support composable functions with non-default parameters in previews by default. To use non-default parameters in previews, you need to annotate your function with the `@PreviewParameter` annotation.

Here's an example of how to use the `@PreviewParameter` annotation to add non-default parameters to your preview:

```
import androidx.compose.runtime.Composable
import androidx.compose.ui.tooling.preview.Preview
import androidx.compose.ui.tooling.preview.PreviewParameter

@Composable
fun MyComposable(message: String, count: Int = 1) {
    repeat(count) {
        Text(text = message)
    }
}

@Preview
@Composable
fun MyComposablePreview(@PreviewParameter(message = "Sample message") message: String, 
                        @PreviewParameter(message = "Sample count") count: Int = 3) {
    MyComposable(message = message, count = count)
}
```

In this example, the `MyComposable` function has two parameters, `message` and `count`, but `count` has a default value of `1`.

To allow these parameters in the preview, we annotate the preview with `@PreviewParameter` and add the `message` and `count` parameters to the preview function. The `@PreviewParameter` annotation takes a `message` parameter that is used when displaying the preview in the Android Studio Preview window.

In the preview function, we pass the annotated parameters to the `MyComposable` function using `message = message` and `count = count`.

Once you have added the `@PreviewParameter` annotation to your function, you should be able to use non-default parameters in your preview.

